32:13.781 --> 32:15.880
Yeah, she wrote
her thesis on...

32:15.882 --> 32:17.616
The Unreliable Narrator!

32:17.618 --> 32:19.451
The Unreliable Narrator.

32:19.453 --> 32:20.820
- What's that?
- My thesis.

32:20.822 --> 32:22.254
Hey, guys, what's up?

32:22.256 --> 32:25.190
Unreliable narrators are
considered a device, right?

32:25.192 --> 32:26.658
Don't answer.
They are. They are.

32:26.660 --> 32:28.494
And they don't get a
lot of literary analysis

32:28.496 --> 32:30.094
because it's a
gimmick, it's a trick.

32:30.096 --> 32:32.630
I mean, "Canterbury Tales"
gets a, gets a shout-out

32:32.632 --> 32:34.265
because, you know, it's good,

32:34.267 --> 32:37.802
but then typically, it's used
for popcorn crime novels

32:37.804 --> 32:39.906
and thriller movies, like
Agatha Christie, Usual Suspects,

32:39.908 --> 32:40.973
- so on and so forth.
- Right.

32:40.975 --> 32:43.675
But I'm gonna argue
that every narrator,

32:43.677 --> 32:46.779
